94
00:04:56,110 --> 00:04:59,969
The second important concept is
the notion of pressure,

95
00:04:59,969 --> 00:05:03,479
the kinetic theory 
shows that we can define the

96
00:05:03,479 --> 00:05:06,580
pressure as a force per units 
of area,

97
00:05:06,580 --> 00:05:11,500
and we can link it to the agitation velocity 
of particles, here,

98
00:05:11,500 --> 00:05:12,499
raised to the power 2,

99
00:05:12,499 --> 00:05:14,300
to the mass of the particles

100
00:05:14,380 --> 00:05:18,920
and to the number of molecules.
Here we have a 1/3 coefficient.

101
00:05:18,920 --> 00:05:20,189
What we can show is,

102
00:05:20,189 --> 00:05:23,190
that when we have, for example, a
wall,

103
00:05:23,190 --> 00:05:27,690
we will have particle agitation and so 
collisions between particles.

104
00:05:27,690 --> 00:05:31,740
These particles will also 
collide with the wall.

105
00:05:31,740 --> 00:05:34,370
This exchange of momentum,

106
00:05:34,370 --> 00:05:36,039
which is unceasing,

107
00:05:36,039 --> 00:05:40,129
will create a force per units of 
area which takes this shape.

108
00:05:40,129 --> 00:05:43,810
I am now going to use a small 
numerical simulation to illustrate

109
00:05:43,810 --> 00:05:45,529
this notion of pressure.

110
00:05:45,529 --> 00:05:47,050
I will consider

111
00:05:47,050 --> 00:05:49,219
certain volumes

112
00:05:49,219 --> 00:05:52,159
in which I have a certain 
number of atoms.

113
00:05:52,159 --> 00:05:56,279
I will be able to modify their
velocity and their number. For instance,

114
00:05:56,279 --> 00:05:57,040
if I increase

115
00:05:57,040 --> 00:05:59,119
the number of atoms in this volume,

116
00:05:59,119 --> 00:06:03,029
I increase therefore n, and I will
increase the pressure.

117
00:06:03,029 --> 00:06:06,740
Now, the agitation velocity, 
so the temperature,

118
00:06:06,740 --> 00:06:10,999
I will also increase the pressure.

119
00:06:10,999 --> 00:06:13,719
If now I decrease the volume,

120
00:06:13,719 --> 00:06:17,999
I will increase the number 
of molecule per units of volume.

121
00:06:17,999 --> 00:06:18,689
There again,

122
00:06:18,689 --> 00:06:21,770
I am increasing the pressure.

123
00:06:21,770 --> 00:06:24,400
This relatively simple simulation

124
00:06:24,400 --> 00:06:25,889
highlights how

125
00:06:25,889 --> 00:06:28,900
the pressure, which will also
be a macroscopic measure,

126
00:06:28,900 --> 00:06:34,400
is linked to the molecular scale
from the particles’ agitation.

127
00:06:34,400 --> 00:06:36,619
So far, we have done

128
00:06:36,619 --> 00:06:40,349
a little bit of kinetic theory to
get a conceptual

129
00:06:40,349 --> 00:06:41,610
idea,

130
00:06:41,610 --> 00:06:42,410
a theoretical idea,

131
00:06:42,410 --> 00:06:45,069
of what a gas is at the molecular scale.

132
00:06:45,069 --> 00:06:48,679
Now we will try to 
establish more factual elements

133
00:06:48,679 --> 00:06:51,169
taken from experimental observations.

134
00:06:51,169 --> 00:06:54,710
The first experimental results
are due to an Englishman

135
00:06:54,710 --> 00:06:56,499
called Robert Boyle

136
00:06:56,499 --> 00:06:58,360
in 1662.

137
00:06:58,360 --> 00:07:03,129
What Boyle noticed is that the
product between the pressure

138
00:07:03,129 --> 00:07:05,379
and the volume is constant.

139
00:07:05,379 --> 00:07:06,550
This result

140
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:10,229
will be obtained independently a few
years later by

141
00:07:10,229 --> 00:07:11,430
Edme Mariotte,

142
00:07:11,430 --> 00:07:13,550
in 1676.

143
00:07:13,550 --> 00:07:14,650
A couple of years

144
00:07:14,650 --> 00:07:18,360
after, Guillaume Amontons
redoing

145
00:07:18,360 --> 00:07:22,840
the same type of experiments showed that
this law pV = constant

146
00:07:22,840 --> 00:07:26,639
is only valid if the temperature remains 
constant. Right before the French

147
00:07:26,639 --> 00:07:32,180
revolution, Jacques Charles came by
what we call the law of volumes,

148
00:07:32,180 --> 00:07:37,259
This law states that the ratio between
pressure and temperature is

149
00:07:37,259 --> 00:07:38,749
a unique function

150
00:07:38,749 --> 00:07:40,469
of volume.

151
00:07:40,469 --> 00:07:44,619
Joseph Gay-Lussac, during the
First Empire, obtained the law of

152
00:07:44,619 --> 00:07:47,630
pressures, which is a variant
of the law of volumes

153
00:07:47,630 --> 00:07:51,599
and that simply states that the ratio 
between volume over temperature

154
00:07:51,599 --> 00:07:53,309
is a function of pressure.

155
00:07:53,309 --> 00:07:58,479
Finally, we owe to Avogadro the
following results, that is

156
00:07:58,479 --> 00:08:02,490
the volume of a gas is proportional
to the number of particles

157
00:08:02,490 --> 00:08:08,330
per unit of volume (i.e. n) and this, 
for a given temperature and pressure.

158
00:08:08,330 --> 00:08:12,509
If I now try to 
sum up all these

159
00:08:12,509 --> 00:08:13,479
results here.

160
00:08:13,479 --> 00:08:15,260
I obtain the following relation:

161
00:08:15,260 --> 00:08:17,610
pV / nT

162
00:08:17,610 --> 00:08:19,909
is equal to a constant.

163
00:08:19,909 --> 00:08:21,449
We will see that this constant

164
00:08:21,449 --> 00:08:25,879
is the ideal gas constant.
Let’s now resume all these

165
00:08:25,879 --> 00:08:28,759
results.
We first pointed out

166
00:08:28,759 --> 00:08:32,849
thanks to kinetic theory
that at the molecular scale, we could

167
00:08:32,849 --> 00:08:34,580
define pressure

168
00:08:34,580 --> 00:08:35,980
as

169
00:08:35,980 --> 00:08:40,810
the product of the number of molecules or
the number of particles per volume,

170
00:08:40,810 --> 00:08:44,480
their mass, multiplied by the
agitation velocity

171
00:08:44,480 --> 00:08:45,290
squared.

172
00:08:45,290 --> 00:08:48,399
A the macroscopic scale, 
we used the results

173
00:08:48,399 --> 00:08:52,670
of experimental observations and 
obtained that the product between

174
00:08:52,670 --> 00:08:54,850
the pressure and the velocity is linked

175
00:08:54,850 --> 00:08:55,980
to the temperature,

176
00:08:55,980 --> 00:08:59,820
the number of moles, i.e. the number
of molecules divided by the

177
00:08:59,820 --> 00:09:01,000
Avogadro constant.

178
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:06,200
A constant appeared called
the ideal gas constant.

179
00:09:06,200 --> 00:09:12,720
We also introduce Boltzmann
constant, and we can link the

180
00:09:12,720 --> 00:09:16,310
ideal gas constant to Boltzmann’s
constant and the Avogadro constant.

181
00:09:16,310 --> 00:09:19,840
We are now able to
link the pressure defined

182
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:21,420
at a microscopic scale

183
00:09:21,420 --> 00:09:24,410
to the pressure defined at the 
macroscopic scale.

184
00:09:24,410 --> 00:09:28,160
At the microscopic scale, or molecular
scale, kinetic theory has

185
00:09:28,160 --> 00:09:31,510
showed that the pressure 
is linked to the mass of molecules,

186
00:09:31,510 --> 00:09:36,160
to their number per unit volume, and
to the square of the agitation velocity.

187
00:09:36,160 --> 00:09:40,500
The experimental observations have
led to the ideal gas law,

188
00:09:40,500 --> 00:09:42,730
that states that the product

189
00:09:42,730 --> 00:09:44,410
pressure times volume

190
00:09:44,410 --> 00:09:45,710
is equal

191
00:09:45,710 --> 00:09:49,000
to the temperature times the 
ideal gas constant

192
00:09:49,000 --> 00:09:52,700
times the number of moles.
If I now equalize both expressions

193
00:09:52,700 --> 00:09:54,500
for the pressure,

194
00:09:54,500 --> 00:09:58,290
at the macroscopic scale and at 
the microscopic scale, I obtain

195
00:09:58,290 --> 00:09:59,430
the following relation:

196
00:09:59,430 --> 00:10:03,720
which after simplification, allows me to 
compute the agitation velocity

197
00:10:03,720 --> 00:10:05,960
as a function of temperature.

198
00:10:05,960 --> 00:10:07,189
This relation

199
00:10:07,189 --> 00:10:11,009
marks a link between what is 
happening at the macroscopic scale and

200
00:10:11,009 --> 00:10:13,729
at the microscopic scale. The
temperature is a macroscopic

201
00:10:13,729 --> 00:10:15,040
quantity,

202
00:10:15,040 --> 00:10:18,440
and we see that as we increase the 
temperature,

203
00:10:18,440 --> 00:10:22,160
the agitation velocity at 
the molecular scale increases.

204
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:24,279
Inversely, if the temperature decreases,

205
00:10:24,279 --> 00:10:27,710
the agitation velocity of the particles
decreases at the molecular scale.

206
00:10:27,710 --> 00:10:32,010
To get an idea of the orders of magnitude,
we will consider the numerical

207
00:10:32,010 --> 00:10:32,689
application,

208
00:10:32,689 --> 00:10:35,430
We are going to take a gas, 
say nitrogen,

209
00:10:35,430 --> 00:10:40,800
whose molar mass is 14 g/mol. 
Normally, this is a so-called

210
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:41,649
atomic gas,

211
00:10:41,649 --> 00:10:45,130
I will here try to treat it as a 
simple gas.

212
00:10:45,130 --> 00:10:48,710
We are also working at atmospheric
pressure and at ambient

213
00:10:48,710 --> 00:10:49,730
room temperature,

214
00:10:49,730 --> 00:10:53,550
i.e. a temperature of 
20 degree Celsius or

215
00:10:53,550 --> 00:10:57,270
293 Kelvins. The number of atoms

216
00:10:57,270 --> 00:11:00,360
per unit of volume in this case
is given by

217
00:11:00,360 --> 00:11:03,200
the ideal gas law. In this way.
We thus find that n

218
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:05,370
is of the order of magnitude of 10^25

219
00:11:05,370 --> 00:11:09,500
atoms/m^3.

220
00:11:09,800 --> 00:11:12,700
If we now use the previous 
relation

221
00:11:12,700 --> 00:11:15,720
which linked agitation velocity to
the temperature,

222
00:11:15,720 --> 00:11:19,100
we find that even 
if the gas is at rest,

223
00:11:19,100 --> 00:11:23,800
the agitation velocity of the molecules
 is of the order of 720m/s,

224
00:11:23,800 --> 00:11:26,560
a velocity that is extremely
big.

225
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:29,820
We will now approach the last
point concerning the physical

226
00:11:29,820 --> 00:11:33,740
properties of simple bodies, 
that is the notion of change of state.

227
00:11:33,740 --> 00:11:39,000
For that, I will work in a 3 dimensional 
space with pressure,

228
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:41,470
volume and temperature.

229
00:11:41,470 --> 00:11:45,509
In this space, liquids will 
occupy a certain part,

230
00:11:45,509 --> 00:11:49,720
gases will occupy another, 
and solids

231
00:11:49,720 --> 00:11:50,920
will also occupy

232
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:54,649
a certain space. We have transition
spaces where we can have

233
00:11:54,649 --> 00:11:58,820
both solids and liquids,

234
00:11:58,820 --> 00:12:01,910
or else here, solids and gas.

235
00:12:01,910 --> 00:12:02,850
So to

236
00:12:02,850 --> 00:12:06,300
understand a little better what is happening, 
we will work at constant

237
00:12:06,300 --> 00:12:07,300
temperature

238
00:12:07,300 --> 00:12:11,220
and we will see what happens when we 
change either the pressure or the volume.

239
00:12:11,220 --> 00:12:13,300
This actually amounts to doing a slice,

240
00:12:13,310 --> 00:12:16,030
here, by taking a constant 
temperature.

241
00:12:16,030 --> 00:12:20,139
To give an example of what is 
happening, I will use once again

242
00:12:20,139 --> 00:12:24,949
